### Key Findings

- **Root cause confirmed**: `RAILWAY_TOKEN` in GitHub Actions secrets has expired/been revoked — the CI validation step calls `{me{id}}` on Railway's GraphQL API and gets "Not Authorized". This is the same failure as PRs #749 and #750.
- **Token type**: The workflow requires an account-scoped or workspace-scoped token (not a project token) because it calls a `me{}` query. Railway recommends workspace-scoped tokens for CI/CD over account-scoped tokens.
- **Static tokens have no documented TTL**: Railway's dashboard-created tokens don't have a scheduled expiry — the recurring revocations are likely triggered by account security events (password changes, session invalidations).
- **Fix is well-documented**: `DEPLOYMENT_SECRETS.md` already has the exact rotation procedure — create a new token at [railway.com/account/tokens](https://railway.com/account/tokens), then `gh secret set RAILWAY_TOKEN --repo alexsiri7/reli`.

### Gaps

- No Railway audit log access to confirm what account event keeps triggering the revocation across three incidents (#749, #750, #752).
- No Railway-native mechanism for proactive token health monitoring found — a cron-based pre-flight check would require custom implementation.
